Introduction:

The box office market share is expected to increase by USD 21.25 billion from 2020 to 2025, and the markets growth momentum will accelerate at a CAGR of 21.78% (Technavio, 2021). The increase in the number of movie screens, the surging success of movies due to the increasing use of animation, and growing international collaboration in film making will offer immense growth opportunities.

In this report I will analyse the relationships between box office, economic, population trends and do the model prediction movie revenue.

Task 3. Data Cleaning & Transformation

# Box Office Dataset

# Convert Rating to numeric (remove "/10")
box_office$Rating_num <- suppressWarnings(as.numeric(sub("/10", "", box_office$Rating)))

# Count before filtering
before_box <- nrow(box_office)

# Clean and filter missing values
box_office_clean <- box_office %>%
  select(-Release.Group, -Genres, -Original_Language, -Rating) %>%
  filter(!is.na(Rating_num), !is.na(Vote_Count))

# Count after filtering and calculate % dropped
after_box <- nrow(box_office_clean)
drop_box <- (before_box - after_box) / before_box * 100
message(sprintf("%.1f%% of rows dropped during Box Office cleaning.", drop_box))



# GDP Dataset

# Reshapes the GDP data from wide to long format so each countryyear pair has one row.
# Making it easier to merge, analyse, and plot over time.

gdp_long <- gdp %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = starts_with("X"), names_to = "Year", values_to = "GDP") %>%
  mutate(
    Year = as.integer(gsub("X", "", Year)),
    GDP = as.numeric(GDP)
  )

# Count before and after removing missing GDP
before_gdp <- nrow(gdp_long)
gdp_long <- gdp_long %>% filter(!is.na(GDP))
after_gdp <- nrow(gdp_long)
drop_gdp <- (before_gdp - after_gdp) / before_gdp * 100
message(sprintf("%.1f%% of rows dropped during GDP cleaning.", drop_gdp))



# Population Dataset

# Count before cleaning
before_pop <- nrow(population)

population_clean <- population %>%
  filter(Population != "--") %>%    # remove invalid rows
  mutate(
    Population_num = as.numeric(gsub(",", "", Population)),
    Year = as.integer(Year),
    Country = trimws(Name)
  ) %>%
  select(Country, Year, Population_num) %>%
  filter(!is.na(Population_num))

# Count after and calculate % dropped
after_pop <- nrow(population_clean)
drop_pop <- (before_pop - after_pop) / before_pop * 100
message(sprintf("%.1f%% of rows dropped during Population cleaning.", drop_pop))

Task 4. Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)

General picture and some focussing data

# Box Office: Boxplot with outliers 

ggplot(box_office_clean, aes(y = X.Worldwide)) +
  geom_boxplot(fill = "lightblue", color = "darkgreen", outlier.color = "darkgreen", outlier.shape = 16) +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  labs(title = "Boxplot of Worldwide Revenue",
       y = "Worldwide Revenue (USD)") +
  theme_minimal()

The boxplot of worldwide revenue shows a highly right-skewed distribution, where most movies earn relatively low revenue while a few blockbusters make exceptionally high amounts.

The long upper tail and numerous outliers indicate that a small number of films dominate the global box office. This highlights large inequality in revenue distribution.

# Box Office: Histogram (log scale) 

ggplot(box_office_clean, aes(x = log10(X.Worldwide))) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 40, fill = "lightgreen", color = "white") +
  labs(title = "Distribution of Worldwide Revenue (Log10 Scale)",
       x = "Log10 Revenue (USD)", y = "Count") +
  theme_minimal()

After applying a log10 transformation to worldwide revenue, the distribution becomes approximately bell-shaped, indicating that most movies earn moderate revenues, while extremely high or low values are comparatively rare. This transformation reduces the impact of extreme outliers seen in the raw scale and helps reveal the central tendency of global box-office performance.

In other words, the film revenue data roughly follows a log-normal pattern, typical in financial datasets where growth compounds over time and a few blockbusters dominate overall earnings.

# Annotate Top 5 Outliers 

top_movies <- box_office_clean %>%
  arrange(desc(X.Worldwide)) %>%
  slice(1:5)

ggplot(box_office_clean, aes(x = Year, y = X.Worldwide)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.4, color = "grey50") +
  geom_point(data = top_movies, aes(x = Year, y = X.Worldwide), color = "red", size = 3) +
  geom_text(data = top_movies, aes(label = Rank), vjust = -1, size = 3, color = "red") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::comma) +
  labs(title = "Top 5 Outlier Movies by Worldwide Revenue",
       y = "Worldwide Revenue (USD)") +
  theme_minimal()

The scatter plot displays worldwide box office revenues over time, with each point representing an individual movie release. Most films are clustered in the lower revenue range, while a few stand out as extreme outliers marked in red, these represent the top five highest-grossing movies worldwide.

The visualization highlights that blockbuster releases tend to occur sporadically across different years, each achieving revenues exceeding USD 2 billion.

This pattern reinforces the skewed nature of the film industry, where a small number of exceptionally successful movies dominate total global earnings, while the majority generate relatively modest revenues.

# GDP: Trends for countries 

gdp_long %>%
  filter(Country.Name %in% c("United States",
                             "United Kingdom",
                             "China",
                             "India",
                             "Australia")) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = Year, y = GDP, color = Country.Name)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.2) +
  scale_y_log10(labels = scales::comma) +
  labs(
    title = "GDP Trends (20002024): Selected Countries",
    x = "Year",
    y = "GDP (log scale)",
    color = "Country"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(legend.position = "right")

The GDP trends from 2000 to 2024 show consistent economic growth across all five countries, but at very different scales. The United States maintains the highest GDP throughout the period, followed by China, which shows the fastest growth, especially after 2005.

India demonstrates steady upward growth, gradually closing the gap with the United Kingdom. Meanwhile, Australia and the United Kingdom exhibit slower but stable growth patterns. Overall, the chart highlights the rapid economic expansion of emerging economies like China and India, while developed economies continue to grow at a more moderate pace.

# Correlation Heatmap 
box_office_num <- box_office_clean %>% select(where(is.numeric))
GGally::ggcorr(box_office_num, label = TRUE, label_round = 2)

The correlation heatmap reveals several clear relationships between the key numerical variables in the dataset.

Worldwide revenue is strongly correlated with both domestic and foreign revenue, indicating that movies performing well in one market tend to succeed globally.

Rank shows a strong negative correlation with revenue variables, confirming that higher-ranked films correspond to greater earnings.

Vote count has a moderate positive correlation with worldwide revenue, suggesting that more popular films with higher audience engagement tend to generate higher box-office returns.

In contrast, movie ratings have only a weak link with revenue, showing that good reviews dont always mean high earnings.

Finally, the year variable shows little to no correlation, indicating that revenue patterns remain relatively stable over time rather than trending upward or downward.

Task 5. Feature Engineering

Transforms raw economic and box office data into analytically rich features, allowing direct comparison between a countrys economic prosperity and its film market performance.

By integrating GDP and population data with box office records, this step establishes a foundation for analyzing how economic strength, audience size, and film performance evolve together across different countries and years.

# Country-Level Analysis: Comparing Economic Strength and Film Performance

# Prepare economic data 

# Rename and normalize GDP country names
gdp_country <- gdp_long %>%
  rename(Country = Country.Name)

# Define normalization function (handles inconsistent country labels)
normalize_country <- function(x) {
  # Validate input type
  if (!is.character(x)) stop("Input must be character")
  
  x <- trimws(x)
  x <- recode(x,
    "USA" = "United States",
    "U.S.A." = "United States",
    "United States of America" = "United States",
    "UK" = "United Kingdom",
    "Great Britain" = "United Kingdom",
    "People's Republic of China" = "China",
    "Mainland China" = "China",
    "Republic of India" = "India",
    "Republic of Korea" = "South Korea"
  )
  return(x)
}

# Apply normalization once to all datasets
gdp_country$Country <- normalize_country(gdp_country$Country)
population_clean$Country <- normalize_country(population_clean$Country)

# Merge GDP and population data 
econ_country <- gdp_country %>%
  left_join(population_clean, by = c("Country", "Year")) %>%
  mutate(
    GDP_per_capita = GDP / Population_num,
    GDP_growth = (GDP - lag(GDP)) / lag(GDP) * 100,
    Pop_growth = (Population_num - lag(Population_num)) / lag(Population_num) * 100
  )

# Aggregate movie performance by country and year 
box_office_country <- box_office_clean %>%
  group_by(Production_Countries, Year) %>%
  summarise(
    BoxOffice_total = sum(X.Worldwide, na.rm = TRUE),
    Rating_avg = mean(Rating_num, na.rm = TRUE),
    Votes_total = sum(Vote_Count, na.rm = TRUE),
    .groups = "drop"
  ) %>%
  rename(Country = Production_Countries)

# Normalize once for Production_Countries 
box_office_country$Country <- normalize_country(box_office_country$Country)

# Merge film and economic data 
country_merged <- box_office_country %>%
  left_join(econ_country, by = c("Country", "Year")) %>%
  mutate(BoxOffice_per_capita = BoxOffice_total / Population_num)

# Filter target countries
chosen_countries <- c("United States", "United Kingdom", "China", "India", "Australia")

country_filtered <- country_merged %>%
  filter(Country %in% chosen_countries)


# Visualization Section

# GDP per Capita Over Time 
ggplot(country_filtered, aes(x = Year, y = GDP_per_capita, color = Country)) +
  geom_line(size = 1.3) +
  geom_point(size = 2) +
  labs(
    title = "GDP per Capita by Country (20002024)",
    subtitle = "Economic strength comparison across major film-producing nations",

    panel.grid.major.x = element_blank()
  )

# Box Office per Capita Over Time

Task 6. Define Target Variable

# Prepare movie-level features
# Only use movies with valid positive worldwide revenue
movies_features <- box_office_clean %>%
  filter(!is.na(X.Worldwide), X.Worldwide > 0) %>% 
  mutate(
    Revenue_log10 = log10(X.Worldwide + 1)   # log-transform to reduce skewness
  )

# Split into train/test (80/20)
set.seed(42)
idx <- createDataPartition(movies_features$X.Worldwide, p = 0.8, list = FALSE)

train_df <- movies_features[idx, ]
test_df  <- movies_features[-idx, ]

# Define binary target variable (median split on training set)
median_train <- median(train_df$X.Worldwide, na.rm = TRUE)

train_df <- train_df %>%
  mutate(Target = factor(
    ifelse(X.Worldwide >= median_train, "High", "Low"),
    levels = c("Low", "High")
  ))

test_df <- test_df %>%
  mutate(Target = factor(
    ifelse(X.Worldwide >= median_train, "High", "Low"),
    levels = c("Low", "High")
  ))

In this task, the goal is to create a binary target variable that distinguishes movies with high versus low worldwide revenue for classification modeling.

First, the dataset is filtered to include only movies with valid positive revenue values, ensuring meaningful analysis. A new variable, Revenue_log10, is generated by applying a logarithmic transformation to the worldwide revenue, which helps to reduce skewness and make the data more normally distributed for modeling. The dataset is then randomly split into an 80 % training set and a 20 % test set to enable model training and evaluation on separate data.

Finally, a binary factor variable Target is created using the median revenue of the training set as the threshold: movies with revenue above or equal to the median are labeled High, and those below are labeled Low.

This approach ensures a balanced classification problem and allows machine learning models to learn the factors that differentiate high-performing films from lower-performing ones.

Task 8. Null Model (Baseline)

# Define target vectors from created train/test sets
y_train <- train_df$Target
y_test  <- test_df$Target

# Determine the majority (most frequent) class in training data
majority_class <- names(which.max(table(y_train)))

# Predict the majority class for all test samples (baseline)
pred_null <- factor(
  rep(majority_class, length(y_test)),
  levels = levels(y_test)
)

# Evaluate baseline model using confusion matrix
cm_null <- confusionMatrix(pred_null, y_test, positive = "High")

Task 9. Train Models

train and compare different machine learning models

training models to predict whether a movie will be a High- or Low-revenue movie using the prepared economic and box-office features.

In the feature selection stage, multiple variables (including X.Domestic, X.Foreign, and Revenue_log10) showed strong relevance to box office performance, as seen in the importance chart.

However, since these variables are directly related to the target (revenue), including them in the predictive model would introduce data leakage.Therefore, only Rating_num, Vote_Count, and Year were retained for the final classification model. These features capture audience sentiment, popularity, and temporal trends, factors that can realistically predict revenue outcomes before knowing the actual earnings.

# Predictor features
features <- c("Rating_num", "Vote_Count", "Year")

x_train <- train_df[, features, drop = FALSE]
y_train <- train_df$Target
x_test  <- test_df[, features, drop = FALSE]
y_test  <- test_df$Target


set.seed(42)
fit_tree <- train(
  x = x_train, y = y_train,
  method = "rpart",
  trControl = trainControl(
    method = "cv",
    number = 3,
    classProbs = TRUE,
    summaryFunction = twoClassSummary
  ),
  metric = "ROC",
  tuneLength = 10
)


# Logistic Regression

set.seed(42)
fit_logit <- train(
  x = x_train, y = y_train,
  method = "glm",
  family = binomial(),
  trControl = trainControl(
    method = "cv",
    number = 3,
    classProbs = TRUE,
    summaryFunction = twoClassSummary
  ),
  metric = "ROC"
)


# Create Predictions 

# Decision Tree
pred_tree_prob  <- predict(fit_tree,  x_test, type = "prob")[, "High"]

# Logistic Regression
pred_logit_prob <- predict(fit_logit, x_test, type = "prob")[, "High"]

In this task, two classification models are trained and compared to predict whether a movie belongs to the High or Low revenue category based on selected predictor variables (Rating_num, Vote_Count, and Year).

The first model uses a Decision Tree (rpart) algorithm, which identifies simple hierarchical rules for classifying movies, while the second model employs a Logistic Regression approach, which estimates the probability of a movie achieving high revenue using a linear combination of features.

Both models are trained using 3-fold cross-validation to improve generalization and prevent overfitting, with ROC (Receiver Operating Characteristic) used as the performance metric.

After training, predictions are generated for the test set, providing probability estimates for each movie being classified as High-revenue.

Task 10. Model Evaluation

roc_tree  <- roc(response = y_test, predictor = pred_tree_prob, levels = c("Low", "High"))
roc_logit <- roc(response = y_test, predictor = pred_logit_prob, levels = c("Low", "High"))

# Plot Decision Tree
plot(
  roc_tree,
  col = "green",
  lwd = 3.5,                          
  main = "ROC Curves: Tree vs Logistic",
  cex.main = 1.3,                 
  cex.lab = 1.1,
  cex.axis = 1.1,
  legacy.axes = TRUE
)

# Logistic Regression
plot(
  roc_logit,
  col = "orange",
  lwd = 3.5,                         
  add = TRUE
)


# Add legend
legend(
  "bottomright",
  legend = c(
    sprintf("Decision Tree (AUC = %.3f)", auc(roc_tree)),
    sprintf("Logistic Regression (AUC = %.3f)", auc(roc_logit))
  ),
  col = c("green", "orange"),
  lwd = 4,                         
  cex = 1.1,                        
  bty = "n"
)

The Decision Tree (green) achieved an AUC of 0.818, correctly distinguishing between High and Low revenue movies about 81.8% of the time. It captures some non-linear relationships but produces a less smooth boundary.

Logistic Regression (orange) performed slightly better with an AUC of 0.846, indicating strong predictive power and stable generalization.

Both ROC curves lie well above the diagonal (AUC = 0.5), confirming that both models perform significantly better than random chance.

Manual feature selection was consistent with automated variable importance from the tree model, reinforcing confidence that the chosen predictors drive both models strong classification results.

Task 11. Model Interpretation with LIME

suppressPackageStartupMessages({
  library(lime)
  library(ggplot2)
  library(dplyr)
  library(stringr)
})

# Hooks for caret models
model_type.train <- function(x, ...) "classification"
predict_model.train <- function(x, newdata, type, ...) {
  as.data.frame(predict(x, newdata, type = "prob"))
}

# Predictors used in your logistic regression model
features_used <- c("Rating_num", "Vote_Count", "Year")

# Build the LIME explainer
explainer_logit <- lime(
  x = x_train[, features_used, drop = FALSE],
  model = fit_logit,
  bin_continuous = TRUE,
  n_bins = 10
)

# Pick two test cases 
cases_to_explain <- c(20, 88)
to_explain <- x_test[cases_to_explain, features_used, drop = FALSE]

# Generate explanations for each model-predicted class
explanation <- lime::explain(
  x = to_explain,
  explainer = explainer_logit,
  n_labels = 1,
  n_features = 5,
  n_permutations = 1000
)

# Build multi-line facet labels for each case
explanation <- explanation %>%
  mutate(
    strip_title = paste0(
      "Case: ", case, "\n",
      "Label: ", label, "\n",
      "Probability: ", sprintf("%.2f", label_prob), "\n",
      "Explanation Fit: ", sprintf("%.2f", model_r2)
    ),
    direction = ifelse(feature_weight > 0, "Supports", "Contradicts")
  )

# Plot 
ggplot(
  explanation,
  aes(x = feature_weight,
      y = reorder(feature, feature_weight),
      fill = direction)
) +
  geom_col(width = 0.7) +
  facet_wrap(~ strip_title, ncol = 2, scales = "free_y") +
  scale_fill_manual(
    name = "Effect on Prediction",
    values = c("Supports" = "lightgreen", "Contradicts" = "lightpink"),
    labels = c("Supports 'High' Revenue", "Contradicts 'High' Revenue")
  ) +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 15) +
  theme(
    strip.text = element_text(
      face = "bold",
      size = 10.5,
      lineheight = 1.15,
      hjust = 0.5,
      vjust = 0.5,
      margin = margin(t = 8, b = 8)
    ),
    strip.background = element_rect(fill = "white", colour = "gray", linewidth = 0.5),
    axis.title.y = element_blank(),
    axis.title.x = element_text(face = "bold", size = 13),
    plot.title = element_text(face = "bold", size = 17, hjust = 0.5),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 12, colour = "darkgray", hjust = 0.5),
    legend.position = "bottom",
    legend.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
    panel.spacing = unit(1.4, "lines"),
    plot.margin = margin(25, 45, 25, 45)
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "LIME Explanation for Logistic Predictions",

  )

The plot shows how LIME decomposes the logistic regression models decisions for two individual movies.
